Independent Variables¶

1. There are 18 independent variables, if we remove 'class'.¶
2. All these 18 independent variables are float64 & int64.¶
3. We need to check the distribution of Independent Variables for Univariate Analysis¶
4. We need to check correlation of features for bivariate analysis.¶

Challeges :-¶

It is possible to have high correlation betweeen different featurs and hence we need to find out features with high correlation and drop the highly correlated independent feature.

Also, it is possible that many of the independent variables are not normally distributed and that can skew the model output. So, we need to transform the independent variables to normal distribution.

Approach for Feature Engineering :-¶

Our approach here will be a Two Layer approach.

First we will not directly start making changes in the features. We will first directly go for implementing and fitting models. We will find Accuracies and Cross_val score of models without doing any feature Engineering.

In second stage, we will do all the feature Engineering and then we will try to find out the accuracies and cross_val scores after implementing feature Engineering.

And then we will compare the accuracies of the models before and after feature engineering to find out whehther the feature Engineering is needed or not.

Dependent Variable¶

As we can see that the data is not balanced.

There are three classes in Dependent Variables(viz: Car,Bus,Van) and out of this one class has around 50% of the data and another two classes have 25% of the data each.

First we will check the accuracy of the models without making any change in the data imbalance. We may try to balance the data only if we are not able to find good accuracy with current state of data imbalance.

In [24]:
corr_thresh=[0.6,0.7,0.8,0.9]
In [25]:
length_drop_columns=[]
for threshold in corr_thresh:
     thresh_columnList=[]
     thresh_indices = np.where(correl > threshold)
     thresh_indices1 = [(correl.index[x], correl.columns[y]) for x, y in zip(*thresh_indices) if x != y and x < y]
     for k in range(len(thresh_indices1)):
             thresh_columnList.append(thresh_indices1[k][0])
     unique_features=np.unique(thresh_columnList)
     length_un_features=len(unique_features)
     length_drop_columns.append(length_un_features)

SVM_after_drop_columns 0.909449 0.944882 [0.9134, 0.9213, 0.8819, 0.937, 0.9646]

Above is the DataFrame for comparison of SVM model

The table above gives model accuracies before PCA and after PCA and also after doing feature engineering and dropping few columns

As we can see from above table that, SVM test accuracy for "test_acc_before_gridsearch" is highest for the SVM model before performing PCA.

Same is also true for "test_acc_after_gridsearch." Accuracy for SVM model before PCA is highest.

All this points to one truth, that performing PCA or performing feature engineering by dropping highly correlated columns only drops the accuracies.

This happens because in both(PCA and feature engineering of dropping columns) we are acutally losing some information which plays a role in getting higher accuracy.

But there is a twist:- If we check the range of "cross_valdtn_scores" a.k.a Cross-Validation-Scores for all the three models we see that for models "SVM_after_PCA" & "SVM_after_drop_columns" the highest accuracy is 96.46%.

Also, the highest accuracy for model "SVM_before_PCA" is 98%.

Not much information is lost when we do feature engineering and drop 8 columns. Hence dropping columns can be a valid option. We have dropped 8 columns and hence the total columns used as the input to model is 10(after dropping the Dependent Variable).

Conclusion: In the table we see that for the last two models, accuracy is 96.46% which is just 1.5% less than the model "SVM_before_PCA."

Best model is the SVM model after PCA as the accuracy loss is only 1.5% but the components we have used for PCA is only 8 ."
